1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:23,000
Today is Saturday, March 9, 2013. My name is Willie Griffin and I am a research associate with the Southern oral history program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

3
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:33,000
I am with videographer John Bishop in Albany, Georgia on the campus of Albany State University to conduct an interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

4
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:41,000
which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

5
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:50,000
We are here today with Miss Mary Jones. Thank you so much for being here, Mrs. Jones, and agreeing to share your story with the Civil Rights History Project.

6
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:58,000
I just want to begin by asking you simply where were you born and when were you born?

7
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:07,000
I was born in Georgia, in the 1930s.

8
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,000
1933? Yes.

9
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Okay.

10
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:14,000
In other words, July of 24, 1933.

11
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Okay. So what was it like to grow up in Albany?

12
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Boy, it was kind of rough. I enjoyed it, but it was kind of rough in those days.

13
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:33,000
I lived on a farm see" and a lot of work to do.

14
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:43,000
A lot of excitement too, I would say.

15
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:47,000
My grandmother, who reared me.

16
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:49,000
What was her name?

17
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:55,000
Bertha McIntosh. Bertha McIntosh, okay.

18
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:57,000
Okay.

19
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:03,000
Now, my mother's name, you have that already, I do.

20
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:09,000
But anyway, that was their place that I grew up on. My grandmother's place.

21
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Because of full pants, they bought that little slot of land.

22
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:15,000
We call it slot-loan.

23
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:17,000
Slot-loan.

24
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:19,000
Yeah, slot.

25
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Okay.

26
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:26,000
And so I grew up on that little slot.

27
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:27,000
Okay.

28
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:33,000
And we knew a lot about going to church.

29
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:39,000
And when you work during the weekend and you work at church on Sundays.

30
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:49,000
And from there on too, when I got large enough to really go out and work on the farm,

31
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:57,000
the white man's farm, like gathering peanuts and picking cotton and digging potatoes.

32
00:02:57,000 --> 00:02:59,000
Right.

33
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:03,000
Is we call it pulling corn.

34
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,000
Also pecans gathering pecans.

35
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:13,000
We couldn't go to school when school started like in September.

36
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:17,000
We had to stay together at the farm.

37
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:21,000
And then after you gather the farm, then you could go to school.

38
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:27,000
And that was around about October, November.

39
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:29,000
So you missed the first two months of school?

40
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:31,000
Yeah.

41
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:35,000
And so when you started doing this type of work, how old were you?

42
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:37,000
How young were you when you first started?

43
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:41,000
I probably was about eight.

44
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:49,000
And my grandmother would let me go with this old lady, Miss Alice Porter.

45
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:55,000
And she would take quite a few of the children from the neighborhood.

46
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,000
How to do that kind of work in everything.

47
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:03,000
See, they trusted her because she had children.

48
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:05,000
She didn't play.

49
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:07,000
She was a taskmaster.

50
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:08,000
Yes.

51
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:13,000
But I loved her because she was always so sweet. She kept us in line.

52
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:23,000
So after eight years old, then that was our job, like going out.

53
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:31,000
And sometimes before the farm got ready, we would do a whole and bird seed.

54
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:33,000
hoeing.

55
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,000
Yeah, hoeing.

56
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:37,000
Explain that. What is that?

57
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:45,000
That's like a whether Mr. Kina, who used to be the mayor here.

58
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:49,000
He had a little farm behind I was.

59
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,000
And he would plant bird seeds.

60
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:52,000
Okay.

61
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:56,000
And they would come up and we had to hoe the grass from around him.

62
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:59,000
And it was real exciting.

63
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Oh, he paid us pretty good.

64
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:02,000
Okay.

65
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,000
Like maybe 75 cents.

66
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:06,000
Okay.

67
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:08,000
So that was good.

68
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
That was a lot of money.

69
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:16,000
And we would save that money like that to help buy school clothes and that.

70
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:17,000
Okay.

71
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:27,000
So what your typical day, your typical work day for an eight year old child is like how long?

72
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:35,000
I say that when we try to get out there before the sun come up because it'd be so hot.

73
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:41,000
So I would say around about seven o'clock.

74
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:42,000
Okay.

75
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:46,000
And they would have food for us to eat.

76
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:47,000
Okay.

77
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:51,000
So we didn't have to worry about taking lunches.

78
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:54,000
And we would worry about five.

79
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:55,000
Five.

80
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:58,000
And they have to know.

81
00:05:58,000 --> 00:05:59,000
So I said.

82
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:01,000
And it was in walking distance.

83
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:02,000
Okay.

84
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:07,000
So we would get together and all of us lived at right right in the same neighborhood.

85
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:14,000
So we would get together and walk back to the house that wasn't too far.

86
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:19,000
So we didn't need a chef around like we did Miss Alice Porter.

87
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:24,000
we went out to do peanuts and cotton and all of that.

88
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:28,000
Because we all lived at right in neighborhood.

89
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:29,000
Okay.

90
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:32,000
So we talked a little bit about when you finally did.

91
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:37,000
Once the season was over and it was time to pick the crops and you finally got into school.

92
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:40,000
What was the school, what were the schools like?

93
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:44,000
The school was when we first started in the church.

94
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:47,000
First but third is the Baptist church.

95
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:52,000
It's one of the oldest churches in the Southwest Georgia.

96
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:58,000
It's like a new boss, a tenant at church.

97
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Visited rather.

98
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:01,000
W.V. Du Bois?

99
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:02,000
Wow.

100
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:03,000
Okay.

101
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:06,000
And he was so excited about it about how it was.

102
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:11,000
It was a grid big of something like a bond that the white folks had given us.

103
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:12,000
Okay.

104
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:13,000
That we could use.

105
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:17,000
They used it first and they built them a church and they gave that to us.

106
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:18,000
Okay.

107
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,000
So.

108
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:25,000
So that they had special classrooms or did you just hold church like in the...

109
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:28,000
Hold, it was the whole building.

110
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:29,000
Okay.

111
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,000
You know, in different areas.

112
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:41,000
Like first through fifth was in this corner and then the other over there up until the seventh grade.

113
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:42,000
Wow.

114
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:45,000
And then we're in a building, a church.

115
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:52,000
And a matter of fact that's where I went to school until I finished seventh grade.

116
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:53,000
Okay.

117
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:54,000
What was in there?

118
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:55,000
But we started in the church.

119
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:56,000
Okay.

120
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:58,000
What was the name of this one that you finished?

121
00:07:58,000 --> 00:07:59,000
Shepherd.

122
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:04,000
We named it after the master that gave us the big church.

123
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:05,000
Oh wow.

124
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:09,000
Because he gave us that ground and stuff so we named it Shepherd.

125
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:10,000
Okay.

126
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:12,000
Elementary school.

127
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:15,000
Okay.

128
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:17,000
So what were the teachers like in the school?

129
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:19,000
Do you have fond memories of them?

130
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:21,000
Yeah, it is like your mama.

131
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:22,000
You like it?

132
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:24,000
You kept you in line.

133
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,000
They kept us in line.

134
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:29,000
And whip you when you did wrong.

135
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:31,000
So you had to step out of line.

136
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:32,000
I tell you.

137
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:33,000
Okay.

138
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:36,000
So do you remember any of the names in the church?

139
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:37,000
Yes.

140
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:41,000
Miss Willime Jackson was my first grade teacher through third.

141
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:42,000
Okay.

142
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:43,000
Uh-huh.

143
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:49,000
So what type of student were you?

144
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:52,000
Did you like going to school for the social party?

145
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:53,000
Yeah.

146
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:54,000
And for the academics.

147
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:58,000
Well you go ahead and use going to get that because it's going to make you get your lesson.

148
00:08:58,000 --> 00:08:59,000
Right.

149
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:06,000
And from fourth through seventh it was Miss Celeste Scott.

150
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:07,000
Miss Celeste Scott.

151
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:09,000
Uh-huh.

152
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:11,000
Okay.

153
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:15,000
So after seventh grade you went on to high school?

154
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:17,000
Came to our old building.

155
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:19,000
You had to come to our old building then.

156
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:21,000
Okay.

157
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:23,000
And how was that?

158
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:25,000
I mean it was a big change, I imagine.

159
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:32,000
Yeah, that was a big change because we had to find, you know, like some of your relatives

160
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:34,000
or some to stay with.

161
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:40,000
Unless you could get your ride back home, maybe they were with people who was working up here

162
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:41,000
and all being.

163
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:43,000
But I stayed with my aunt.

164
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:44,000
Uh-huh.

165
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:50,000
My three cousins and myself lived with my aunt Ella Holloway.

166
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:51,000
Ella Holloway?

167
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:52,000
Uh-huh.

168
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:54,000
On a chair street.

169
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
Okay.

170
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:58,000
And was that in the primary black community?

171
00:09:58,000 --> 00:09:59,000
Was that in Harlem?

172
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:01,000
Yeah, that was in the black community.

173
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:02,000
Okay.

174
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:04,000
Uh-huh.

175
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:12,000
And from the, uh, when I came up here we went to Monroe Comprehensive High School, which is still open to the day.

176
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:13,000
Okay.

177
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:14,000
Uh-huh.

178
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:21,000
What do you recall about Monroe?

179
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:22,000
What was it?

180
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:23,000
Oh, I lived in Monroe.

181
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:24,000
I was into sports.

182
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:25,000
Okay.

183
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:26,000
Uh-huh.

184
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:30,000
I played basketball, ran track.

185
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:31,000
Oh, wow.

186
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:33,000
So you all around the athlete?

187
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:34,000
Yeah.

188
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:35,000
Okay.

189
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:37,000
And most of my cheer will not.

190
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:38,000
Okay.

191
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:39,000
Uh-huh.

192
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:40,000
Okay.

193
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:41,000
What about you?

194
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:46,000
Um, so you were in high school and then what year did you graduate from high school?

195
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:50,000
Uh, it's supposed to be 51.

196
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:51,000
51.

197
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:55,000
But I was in love and I got married.

198
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:57,000
That's a good reason.

199
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:03,000
And he was going to the arm and the next day or so too.

200
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:04,000
Uh-huh.

201
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:05,000
And so you got married.

202
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,000
And what was your husband's name?

203
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:08,000
Jimmy Lee Jones.

204
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:09,000
Jimmy Lee Jones.

205
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:10,000
Uh-huh.

206
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:11,000
Okay.

207
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:15,000
And how did you meet him?

208
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:16,000
How did he start it?

209
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:18,000
We started at Monroe.

210
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:19,000
He was at Monroe.

211
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:20,000
Okay.

212
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
He's playing football in basketball.

213
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:24,000
And we met like that.

214
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:25,000
Okay.

215
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:32,000
So in 1950, I mean, the schools were, I mean, they were segregated.

216
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:33,000
Yes.

217
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:37,000
And what were the racial conditions like in the 50s in school?

218
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:40,000
Was that something that was on your mind?

219
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:42,000
Were you thinking about race?

220
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:46,000
Did you, how did you navigate that?

221
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:54,000
Well, I had, I had listened to the radio and different things like that and read the

222
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:00,000
paper about it and other citizen thing about this integration.

223
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:04,000
And I read and bought it and kept it with it.

224
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:08,000
And I said, well, if it's hit, I'll be in Georgia.

225
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:12,000
I will show enough beer part of it because I wanted better for my children.

226
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:13,000
Okay.

227
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:21,000
Because see, when my children was old enough to go to public schools, they

228
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:24,000
just integrated in here and all of them.

229
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:27,000
And they went through so much.

230
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:29,000
And really did.

231
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:30,000
Okay.

232
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:33,000
And you said you were reading about the movement, hearing about it.

233
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:35,000
What were your sources?

234
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:42,000
Pittsburgh Courier, put curd and the southwest Georgia, Miss A.C.

235
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:43,000
Sugs.

236
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:44,000
A.C. Searles.

237
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:50,000
Yeah, it was the owner of that paper and did the writing.

238
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:51,000
Okay.

239
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:56,000
What did your children have to go through that?

240
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:01,000
Something that's part of the story that doesn't get told much?

241
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:05,000
They first integrated the high schools here.

242
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:06,000
First.

243
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:13,000
And my oldest daughter was, I signed for her to go to second year.

244
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:14,000
Okay.

245
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:17,000
And boy, boy, it was something.

246
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:22,000
The principal, Mr. McNair, he called them little monkeys.

247
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:25,000
Because he said that's all he ever called them.

248
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:28,000
And he couldn't call them nothing else.

249
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:33,000
And they would have almost a ride every day.

250
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:37,000
And today I do not understand.

251
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:38,000
Okay.

252
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:44,000
Why didn't any, why didn't too many telephones then in the home?

253
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:48,000
And we didn't have our cell phone.

254
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:55,000
But every time it starts at all being high, those children for money will be dead.

255
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:58,000
I don't know how they got there.

256
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:06,000
But the children got what they didn't want to sit this out of them and you know any cafeteria and all of that.

257
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:13,000
And they were spit at them and call them all kind of names, monkeys and bells.

258
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
And all of that.

259
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:17,000
How did your children respond to this?

260
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:19,000
They, she hung in there.

261
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:21,000
I thought she hung in there.

262
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:28,000
I think it was about one or two that acted kind of nice, whites.

263
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:33,000
But she hung in there because so many of her friends went alone when she did.

264
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:36,000
You know we got them registered and everything.

